# Mantine Menu Component Best Practices

## Core Guidelines

- Use the Menu component for compact navigation or action menus, such as dropdowns for settings, user profiles, or contextual actions, to save screen space and improve usability.
- Keep menu items concise and action-oriented, using clear labels (e.g., "Edit," "Delete") to ensure users understand their purpose at a glance.
- Leverage Menu.Target with interactive elements (e.g., buttons, icons) to trigger the menu, ensuring intuitive access while maintaining accessibility.
- Use Menu.Divider to group related items visually, enhancing readability for menus with multiple sections or categories.
- Implement controlled or uncontrolled modes based on use case—use controlled (opened and onChange) for dynamic behavior, and uncontrolled for simpler, static menus.
- Customize menu appearance with shadow, width, and position props to match your app's design and ensure visibility on different screen sizes.
- Ensure accessibility by adding aria-label to Menu.Target and testing with keyboard navigation (e.g., Tab, Enter, Arrow keys) and screen readers.
- Avoid overloading menus with too many items; use submenus (Menu.Item with nested Menu) sparingly and only for hierarchical actions, keeping the primary menu focused.

## Key Props Reference

### Menu Component Props

| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|------|------|---------|-------------|
| `trigger` | `'hover' \| 'click' \| 'click-hover'` | `'click'` | Controls how the dropdown is triggered - click is most accessible, hover is convenient but less accessible, click-hover works on both desktop and mobile |
| `opened` | `boolean` | - | Controls dropdown opened state |
| `onChange` | `(opened: boolean) => void` | - | Called when dropdown opened state changes |
| `position` | `string` | `'bottom-start'` | Dropdown position relative to target (`bottom`, `top`, `left`, `right` with `-start` or `-end` modifiers) |
| `offset` | `number` | `5` | Dropdown offset from target element in px |
| `closeOnItemClick` | `boolean` | `true` | Determines whether dropdown should be closed when item is clicked |
| `closeOnClickOutside` | `boolean` | `true` | Determines whether dropdown should be closed when user clicks outside of it |
| `shadow` | `string` | `'sm'` | Shadow from theme or any CSS value |
| `width` | `number \| 'target' \| string` | - | Dropdown width, or 'target' to match target width |
| `withArrow` | `boolean` | `false` | Adds an arrow to the dropdown |
| `transitionProps` | `object` | - | Props to customize dropdown transition |
| `loop` | `boolean` | `true` | Whether focus should loop through items when the end/beginning is reached |
| `menuItemTabIndex` | `number` | `-1` | Set to 0 to enable Tab navigation between menu items |

### Menu.Item Props

| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|------|------|---------|-------------|
| `color` | `string` | - | Item color from theme |
| `disabled` | `boolean` | `false` | Disables item |
| `leftSection` | `React.ReactNode` | - | Left section, usually used for icons |
| `rightSection` | `React.ReactNode` | - | Right section, usually used for shortcuts or additional info |
| `component` | `any` | `'button'` | Component used as root element (button, a, div, etc.) |

## Explanation of Recommendations

### Compact Navigation/Action Menus

Use Menus for dropdowns like user settings or contextual actions:

```tsx
import { Menu } from '@mantine/core';

function UserMenu() {
  return (
    <Menu>
      <Menu.Target>
        <button>Profile</button>
      </Menu.Target>
      <Menu.Dropdown>
        <Menu.Item>Settings</Menu.Item>
        <Menu.Item>Logout</Menu.Item>
      </Menu.Dropdown>
    </Menu>
  );
}
```

This saves space and provides quick access to actions.

### Concise Labels

Use short, action-oriented labels like "Edit Profile" or "Delete Item" to avoid confusion:

```tsx
<Menu.Item>Edit Profile</Menu.Item>
```

### Interactive Targets

Use Menu.Target with buttons, icons, or other elements for intuitive triggering:

```tsx
<Menu.Target>
  <IconUserCircle size={24} />
</Menu.Target>
```

### Visual Grouping

Use Menu.Divider to separate related items:

```tsx
<Menu.Dropdown>
  <Menu.Item>Settings</Menu.Item>
  <Menu.Divider />
  <Menu.Item>Logout</Menu.Item>
</Menu.Dropdown>
```

### Controlled vs. Uncontrolled

For dynamic behavior, use controlled mode:

```tsx
const [opened, setOpened] = useState(false);

<Menu opened={opened} onChange={setOpened}>
  {/* Menu items */}
</Menu>
```

For static menus, uncontrolled mode (default opened) is simpler.

### Customization

Adjust shadow, width, and position for design consistency:

```tsx
<Menu shadow="md" width={200} position="bottom-end">
  {/* Menu items */}
</Menu>
```

Test on mobile and desktop to ensure visibility.

### Accessibility

Add aria-label and test with keyboard navigation:

```tsx
<Menu.Target aria-label="User menu">
  <button>User</button>
</Menu.Target>
```

Ensure users can navigate with Arrow keys, Enter, and Space, and verify screen reader compatibility.

### Avoid Overloading

Limit primary menu items to 5–7 for clarity. For more options, use submenus:

```tsx
<Menu>
  <Menu.Target>
    <button>More Actions</button>
  </Menu.Target>
  <Menu.Dropdown>
    <Menu.Item>Action 1</Menu.Item>
    <Menu>
      <Menu.Target>
        <Menu.Item>Advanced</Menu.Item>
      </Menu.Target>
      <Menu.Dropdown>
        <Menu.Item>Sub Action 1</Menu.Item>
      </Menu.Dropdown>
    </Menu>
  </Menu.Dropdown>
</Menu>
```

Use submenus cautiously to avoid complexity.

## Advanced Usage Tips

### Trigger Options

- **Click (default)**: Most accessible option, works on all devices
- **Hover**: Convenient but less accessible, use `openDelay` and `closeDelay` to control timing
- **Click-Hover**: Best of both worlds - works with hover on desktop and click on mobile

```tsx
<Menu trigger="click-hover" openDelay={100} closeDelay={400}>
  {/* Menu content */}
</Menu>
```

### Custom Components as Target

When using custom components as Menu.Target, ensure they properly forward refs:

```tsx
const CustomButton = forwardRef<HTMLButtonElement, ButtonProps>(
  ({ children, ...props }, ref) => (
    <button ref={ref} {...props}>
      {children}
    </button>
  )
);

<Menu>
  <Menu.Target>
    <CustomButton>Custom target</CustomButton>
  </Menu.Target>
  {/* Menu content */}
</Menu>
```

